04318nam a22007095i 9780824861285DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248612857 a10.1515/97808248612852doi  a(DE-B1597)484110  a(OCoLC)1024049454  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL726.2b.S34 2007eb 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.6/1142221 aSchalow, Paul Gordon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Poetics of Courtly Male Friendship in Heian Japan /cPaul Gordon Schalow. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Poems to Sing and the Hope for Transcendence -- tChapter 2. Paradigms of Friendship in the Tale of Ise -- tChapter 3. Poetic Sequences in the Kagerō Diary -- tChapter 4. The Tale of Genji: “Two Cranes Flying Wing to Wing” -- tChapter 5. The Uji Chapters: “Maidens of the Bridge” -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWestern scholars have tended to read Heian literature through the prism of female experience, stressing the imbalance of power in courtship and looking for evidence that women hoped to move beyond the constraints of marriage politics. Paul Schalow’s original and challenging work inherits these concerns about the transcendence of love and carries them into a new realm of inquiry—the suffering of noblemen and the literary record of their hopes for transcendence through friendship. He traces this recurring theme, which he labels "courtly male friendship," in five important literary works ranging from the tenth-century Tale of Ise to the early eleventh-century Tale of Genji.Whether authored by men or women, the depictions of male friendship addressed in this work convey the differing perspectives of male and female authors profoundly shaped by their gender roles in the court aristocracy. Schalow’s analysis clarifies in particular how Heian literature articulates the nobleman’s wish to be known and appreciated fully by another man.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJapanese literatureyHeian period, 794-1185xHistory and criticism. 0aMale friendship in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486128540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824861285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824861285/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK